\begin_layout Standard
The major step up to the minimal model is that we do not consider an homogeneous
 superconductive proximity effect term but instead self-consistently calculate
 for the induced pairing but also magnetization and doping.
 This is realized in a Hartree-Fock-Bogoliubov mean-field theory derived
 in detail in appendix A.
 The mean-field self-energy is realized as a spin-1/2 Hubbard term in the
 Wannier limit through a Hartree-Fock decoupling of a quartic Hamiltonian
 in a Nambu-spinor scheme.
 The obtained total onsite self-energy reads as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{ij}=\frac{1}{2}U\left[\text{Tr}\left(\left[\tau_{z}\otimes\sigma_{0}\right]\tilde{\boldsymbol{\rho}}_{ii}\right)\left[\tau_{z}\otimes\sigma_{0}\right]-2\tilde{\boldsymbol{\rho}}_{ij}\right]\delta_{ij}.\label{eq:Sigma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This term is comprised of both Hartree and Fock self-energies as well as
 the pairing; their Feynman diagrams shown in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:models}}$
\end_inset

)(a).
 Within the Nambu tight-binding scheme, defining the spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\check{c}}_{i}=(c_{i\uparrow}\,\,c_{i\downarrow}\,\,c_{i\uparrow}^{\dagger}\,\,c_{i\downarrow}^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

, the full Hamiltonian matrix reads explicitly as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{H} & =\left(f\delta_{ij}-t\delta_{ij\pm1}\right)\left[\tau_{z}\otimes\sigma_{0}\right]+V_{\text{Z}}\left[\tau_{z}\otimes\sigma_{z}\right]\delta_{ij}\nonumber \\
 & +\frac{\alpha_{\text{R}}}{2a_{0}}\delta_{ij\pm1}^{\pm}\left[\tau_{z}\otimes i\sigma_{y}\right]+\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{ij}\label{eq:H}
\end{align}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $f=2t-\mu$
\end_inset

 the band filling (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=2t$
\end_inset

 corresponding to half and zero filling respectively), 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\eta/a_{0}^{2}$
\end_inset

 the hopping parameter and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 the real-space lattice spacing.
 The Kronecker delta 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 denotes the on-site terms and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ij\pm1}^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 the 1st neighbors hoppings (front and back), and both 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 are Pauli matrices operating in their respectively spin and particle-hole
 subspaces.
 The BdG symmetric object 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\rho}}_{ij}$
\end_inset

, related to the Nambu reduced density matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\rho}_{ij}=\langle\check{\boldsymbol{c}}_{j}^{\dagger}\otimes\check{\boldsymbol{c}}_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

, is defined in appendix A in Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:rhotilde}}$
\end_inset

) and has its underlying spin structure concealed within the bold notation.
 Reiterating, in the Nambu space the significant improvement to the minimal
 model reads as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{0}\left[\tau_{y}\otimes\sigma_{y}\right]\delta_{ij}\rightarrow\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See that the sign of the on-site Hubbard potential 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 dictates the system's state: if, on one hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $U<0$
\end_inset

 then the correlation 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i\uparrow j\downarrow}^{\text{eh}}$
\end_inset

 is favored and the system turns superconductive but, on the other hand,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $U>0$
\end_inset

 then the correlation 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho_{i\uparrow j\uparrow}^{\text{ee}}-\rho_{i\downarrow j\downarrow}^{\text{ee}})/2$
\end_inset

 is instead favored and the system turns ferromagnetic.
 However, although 
\begin_inset Formula $U<0$
\end_inset

 is a prerequisite for a non-zero superconductive correlation it alone does
 not guarantee it; this can be, for example, due to a strong enough Zeeman
 effect that forcefully magnetizes the system.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Schematic models of the hybrid and intrinsic self-consistent Majorana nanowires
 are shown in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:models}}$
\end_inset

)(b).
 The intrinsic model is trivially described by Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:H}}$
\end_inset

), directly incorporating all terms.
 The hybrid system, however, comprises a depleted semiconducting (SM) nanowire
 (bottom in gray) and a doped superconducting (SC) nanowire (top in blue);
 thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\text{SC}}\gg\mu_{\text{SM}}$
\end_inset

.
 Both nanowires are subject to the same Zeeman field but only the SM exhibits
 spin-orbit coupling.
 Crucially, only the SC nanowire contains the self-consistent Hubbard term
 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\text{SC}}$
\end_inset

 (therewith 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\text{SM}}=0$
\end_inset

), thus serving as the sole source of pairing within the system.
 Nevertheless, due to the proximity of the nanowires, there is a possibility
 for Cooper pairs to tunnel through the SC to the SM, effectively inducing
 superconductivity in the SM.
 This proximity effect is modeled by a hopping with intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau<t$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

