\begin_layout Standard
In Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:hybrid}}$
\end_inset

)(a), we present the spectral gap phase diagram 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 versus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 The diagram reveals two distinct regions demarcated by the Pffafian, the
 signature topological invariant also known as Majorana number 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=+1$
\end_inset

 if it's in the trivial phase and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=-1$
\end_inset

 if in the topological phase.
 For general non-interacting systems, the fermionic parity 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 of the ground state of a Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as form 
\begin_inset Formula $P(H)=\text{sgn}(\text{Pf}(A))$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Pf}$
\end_inset

 denotes the Pfaffian of a skew-symmetric matrix 𝐴, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\text{Pf}(A))^{2}=\text{det}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 The topological region takes the form of a hyperboloid, as predicted by
 the minimal model following the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $(V_{\text{Z}}/\Delta_{0})^{2}-(\mu/\Delta_{0})^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 under the assumption of a homogeneous pairing potential.
 Note, however, that the hyperboloid in not centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

, as is the case for the minimal model, but is instead rigidly shifted by
 the self-consistently induced doping.
 Is is relevant to note that, due to the particle-hole symmetries inherited
 from the Nambu formalism, there exists a holeonic phase-transition hyperboloid
 that is mirror-symmetric to the one show, appearing at a larger 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\text{SM}}$
\end_inset

.
 
